$\S$ Define set equality, and verify that it is `reflexive`, `symmetric`, and `transitive`.

First, let us informally define sets and precisely define set membership $\epsilon$. A set is an unordered collection of `objects`, in which the set itself is an object. Set membership is defined as:

$$
  \epsilon : \textbf{Obj} \rightarrow \textbf{Obj} \rightarrow \mathbb{P}
$$

Equality is defined as:

$$
  \begin{matrix}
    A = B \rightarrow &\forall x \in A, x \in B \\
    &\wedge \\
    &\forall x \in B, x \in A
  \end{matrix}
$$

Goals:

$$
  \begin{matrix}
    \textrm{reflexive} & \forall A, A = A \\
    \textrm{symmetric} & \forall A B, A = B \leftrightarrow B = A \\
    \textrm{transitive} & \forall A B C, (A = B) \wedge (B = C) \rightarrow (A = C)
  \end{matrix}
$$

Proofs:

$$
  \begin{matrix}
    A = A & \rightarrow & \forall x \in A, x \in A \rightarrow \top & \textrm{by exact}. \\
    A = B & \rightarrow & \forall x \in A, x \in B & \\
    && \wedge & \\
    && \forall x \in B, x \in A & \\
    & \leftrightarrow & B = A & \textrm{by swapping the arguments of } \wedge. \\
    A = B &&& \\
    \wedge &&& \\
    B = C & \rightarrow & \forall x \in A, x \in B & \textrm{(1)} \\
    && \wedge & \\
    && \forall x \in B, x \in A & \textrm{(2)} \\
    && \wedge & \\
    && \forall x \in B, x \in C & \textrm{(3)} \\
    && \wedge & \\
    && \forall x \in C, x \in B & \textrm{(4)} \\
    & \rightarrow & \forall x \in A, x \in C & \textrm{by (1) and (3)} \\
    && \wedge & \\
    && \forall x \in C, x \in A & \textrm{by (4) and (2)} \\
    & \rightarrow & A = C & \textrm{by exact}.
  \end{matrix}
$$

